[
    {
        "content": "<p>Suppose that we have a linear family of endomorphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi>L</mi><mo>→</mo><mtext>End</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi \\colon L \\to \\text{End}(M)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">End</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L,M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> are two <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span>-modules. (Example: the adjoint representation of a Lie algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>. In this case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M = L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>.)<br>\nThen the characteristic polynomials <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>χ</mi><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\chi_{\\phi(x)}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7858em;vertical-align:-0.3552em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3552em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> have coefficients that are homogeneous polynomials as function of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>. (One way to make this precise: represent <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> on some basis of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>.)</p>\n<p>In Lie theory, the smallest index for which this homogeneous \"coefficient polynomial\" is non-zero is called the <em>rank</em>, and elements <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> whose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>χ</mi><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\chi_{\\phi(x)}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7858em;vertical-align:-0.3552em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3552em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> has a non-zero coefficient at index <code>rank</code> are called <em>regular</em> elements.</p>\n<p>Here is my question: these definitions make sense outside Lie theory for an arbitrary <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span></span></span></span> as above. (Oliver has been very patiently pointing this out to me.)</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Are these concepts used outside of Lie theory?</li>\n<li>If yes, under what names?</li>\n<li>If no, what are reasonable names for these concepts? (I currently have <code>LinearMap.polyRank φ</code> and <code>LinearMap.IsRegular φ x</code>, and I'm not very fond of those names.)</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 434337734,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1713524302
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I only have a moment so a quick remark. Maybe <code>LinearMap.nilpotentRank</code> or <code>LinearMap.nilRank</code> for one of the names since when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> is one-dimensional (so that we really just have a single endomorphism) this number is the dimension of the Fitting 0 component.</p>",
        "id": 434356599,
        "sender_full_name": "Oliver Nash",
        "timestamp": 1713531267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, that is a good suggestion. Should we go with something like <code>LinearMap.IsNilRegular</code> for the other one?</p>",
        "id": 434379994,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1713538579
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, I pushed those names to</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/10628#top\">feat(Algebra/Lie/Rank): the rank of a Lie algebra, and regular elements</a> <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/10628\">#10628</a></p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 434407556,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1713548423
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that some people might call these (or very small variations) determinantal varieties.</p>",
        "id": 434434575,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1713560298
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then you can even have three linear spaces and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi>L</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi \\colon L\\to \\mathscr L(M;N)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.19189em;\">L</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 434479574,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
